msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/alignment.rst:16
msgid ""
"Speeding up copy operations by using :class:`uint` assignment in instead of "
"``memcpy``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/alignment.rst:18
msgid "Guaranteeing safe aligned access for ufuncs/setitem/casting code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/alignment.rst:20
msgid ""
"NumPy uses two different forms of alignment to achieve these goals: \"True "
"alignment\" and \"Uint alignment\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/alignment.rst:23
msgid ""
"\"True\" alignment refers to the architecture-dependent alignment of an "
"equivalent C-type in C. For example, in x64 systems :attr:`float64` is "
"equivalent to ``double`` in C. On most systems, this has either an alignment "
"of 4 or 8 bytes (and this can be controlled in GCC by the option ``malign-"
"double``).  A variable is aligned in memory if its memory offset is a "
"multiple of its alignment. On some systems (eg. sparc) memory alignment is "
"required; on others, it gives a speedup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/alignment.rst:31
msgid ""
"\"Uint\" alignment depends on the size of a datatype. It is defined to be "
"the \"True alignment\" of the uint used by NumPy's copy-code to copy the "
"datatype, or undefined/unaligned if there is no equivalent uint. Currently, "
"NumPy uses ``uint8``, ``uint16``, ``uint32``, ``uint64``, and ``uint64`` to "
"copy data of size 1, 2, 4, 8, 16 bytes respectively, and all other sized "
"datatypes cannot be uint-aligned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/alignment.rst:38
msgid ""
"For example, on a (typical Linux x64 GCC) system, the NumPy :attr:"
"`complex64` datatype is implemented as ``struct { float real, imag; }``. "
"This has \"true\" alignment of 4 and \"uint\" alignment of 8 (equal to the "
"true alignment of ``uint64``)."
msgstr ""

